choices.label: Missions sermon 0-1x per year, missions is featured 1-2 times a year.
Missions sermons 2-3x per year, missions is featured 3-5 times a year.
Missions sermons 3-4x per year, missions is featured 6-8 times a year, missions special service 1x a year.
Missions sermons 5-6x per year, missions featured at least monthly at a worship service, missions special service 1-2x a year.
Missions sermons more than 6x per year, missions is a regular part of each weekly worship service.
Do not see the need and importance to feature global missions.
Church leaders are aware of Great Commission. Not yet covering it within discipleship / cell life.
Believe all Christians are called to missions. Exploring ways to integrate missions into discipleship and engage more members in mission trips.
Missions is actively taught in discipleship, cell and spiritual formation curriculum. Discipleship / cell groups are encouraged to sow and go for short term missions.
Missions are central to spiritual formation, discipleship, mentoring, and ministry in the church. Discipleship / cell groups are actively involved in local and global missions in various ways.
No, interested members are to find their own external missions training.
No, church leaders actively refer interested members to external organisations for missions training.
No, exploring potential missions foundational courses to conduct in-house, or via external ministry.
Yes, either by self-developed or via external ministry. Courses may be extensive in content and duration

Yes, either by self-developed or via external ministry. A wide range of courses, including some that are extensive in content and duration. Actively identify potential missions candidate to join missions discipleship track.
No, interested members are to find their own external missions training.
No, church leaders actively refer interested members to external organisations for missions training.
No, exploring potential short-term missions courses to conduct in-house, or send church members who are interested to join externally
Yes, either by self-developed or via external ministry.
Yes, either by self-developed or via external ministry. Have missions mentorship and preparation journey for strong missions volunteers.
No, interested members to find their own external missions training.
No, church leaders actively refer interested members to external organisations for missions training.
No, exploring potential missions courses to conduct in-house, or via external ministry.
Yes, either by self-developed programme or via external ministry.
Yes, either by self-developed programme or via external ministry. Have missions mentorship and preparation journey for high potential long-term missions candidates.
No ST team in the past 5 years
Sending short-term missions teams every 2-3 years.
Sending short-term missions teams every year, to different overseas ministries on an ad-hoc basis.
Actively sending short-term teams every year with some form of partnership with overseas ministries. (Min Sending Ratio: 1 team / 200 members)

Active annual campaign to recruit, train and send short-term teams. (Min Sending Ratio: 1 team / 100 members) Short-term teams are part of a broader missions strategy, with committed oversight and follow-up by missions leadership.
Not involved with the process of anyone going mid-term
Aware of some mid-term interest and makes referrals to mission agencies or external organisations.
Encourages mid-term going with mission agencies or external organisations as a part of members' missions journey.
Has an in-house mid-term programme or established partnerships with mission agencies or external organisations for members to join.
Active promotion and mobilising of interested candidates from different demographics for mid-term service as an integral part of church's missions strategy.
No history or interest in LT missions
Not yet, but open to and encouraging members for LT missions
Working to send or have sent out at least 1 LT missionary in the past 5 years. Have a few individuals/families interested.
Yes, we do commission and send out LT missionaries. We are gradually cultivating a pipeline of LT candidates. (Min Sending Ratio: 1/150 members)

Yes, we actively commission and send out LT missionaries. We actively cultivate, train a pipeline of LT candidates. We train and send out apostolic teams for specific missions strategy. (Min Sending Raio: 1/75 members)
No, we do not have any member care awareness, structure or policy.
No, missionaries arrange their own care teams. Church acknowledges the need but prefers to outsource care for LT missionaries. Leaders meet with missionaries when they're back in Singapore.

Yes to some extent. Church leadership intentionally checks in with LT missionaries when they return to Singapore. External ministries currently provide member care. Missions committee is exploring in-house care for LT missionaries.

Yes. A church leader is assigned to each missionary/family for periodic check-ins (2-3x a year). Basic member care policy is in place. A care team provides check-in, prayer and logistical support for homefront needs.

Yes. A church leader is assigned to each missionary for periodic check-ins and on-field visits. In-depth member care policies cover evacuation, re-entry, retirement, etc. Care specialists support in areas like finance, trauma, counselling etc.
No member care awareness/ interest.
Some interest, but don't know how to provide care.
Some church members informally check in and care for on field missionaries.
Cell groups care/ pray for missionaries from their cell and provide some homefront/ return support on an ad-hoc basis
Cell groups intentionally and actively care/ pray for missionaries from their cell, and provide homefront/ return support
None/Low focus
Occasional prayer for the world/ global missions.
At least 1x per month. We are trying to mobilise more prayer for nations.
At least 2x per month. We are committed to mobilise church to pray for global missions.
At least 3x per month. Global missions is vital to the church.
None/Low focus
1-2x per year
3-6x per year
Close to monthly (12x per year). Regularly encourage individuals and groups to pray regularly for missions and missionaries.

More than monthly (>12x per year). Special times of prayer/fasting for nations/persecuted church. Prayer guides for global missions available for church/cell/individual settings. Committed prayer groups are set up for specific missions/nations.
Very focused on local church needs, church leadership does not see missions giving as a priority.
Occasional collection for special missions needs e.g. natural disasters, wars, pandemics like COVID-19.
Start to teach congregation to give to local/ overseas missions.
Generous to the needs of missions. Challenge congregation to give willingly and joyfully to the needs of missions.
Actively support global missions, good teaching/ understanding in missions giving, encourage long term sustainability and not creating financial dependency through giving policies.
No missions community
We have informal missions community who gather on their own without involvement of church leadership.
Our missions community gathers 1-2x per year.
Our missions community gathers 3-5x per year.
Our missions community actively gathers 6x per year or more.
No missions mentorship provided.
We do ad-hoc meetings with interested members, initiated by them.
We proactively set up meetings with interested members to listen and explore how to support their missions journey. We discuss potential LT missions involvement possibilities.
We actively monitor and meet up with interested members when needed. We have active ongoing conversations for LT mission involvement / participation.

Leadership is actively aware and monitoring church members' mission progress, through regular meet-ups with key missions volunteers (>=4x per year), and drawing up personal plans for serious candidates.
Low missions focus
Open to missions
Believes that every Christian is called to the Great Commission. Goes on mission trip every 1-2 years
Actively championing missions in church. Goes on mission trips 1-3 times a year.
Actively championing missions on local / international level. Goes on mission trips at least 4 times a year.
No leader with missions focus
A few (1-2 leaders) open to missions
A few (1 or more leaders) championing missions in the church.
Close to half (25%-49%) of leadership is championing missions.
Half or more (>=50%) of leadership is championing missions and go on mission trips at least annually.
No missions committee currently
Currently forming a missions committee
Stable committee, working for 5 years or more
Strong committee with influence in the church
Strong missions committee with strong influence in the church
None
Exploring to start a Missions Dept
>= 1 Missions Staff
Decent Missions Dept (ratio: 1 per 200 members)
Well-staffed Missions Dept (ratio: 1 per 100 members)
No missions policy
Very basic missions policy
Working missions policy
Stable missions policy, reviewing for update
Up-to-date and robust missions policy
No mission trip policy
Very basic mission trip policy
Working mission trip policy
Stable mission trip policy, and potentially reviewing for update
Up-to-date and robust mission trip policy
None
Exploring to create policies
Have working long-term missionary policies
On top of LT 'traditional' missionary policy, starting to develop policies for variety of LT mission workers (e.g. tentmakers, business-as-mission etc.)

Have up-to-date and robust policies for sending a variety of LT mission workers (e.g. tentmaker, business-as-mission), contingency policies, actively exploring policies to promote missions across different generations.
No active relationship
Starting to engage
Working relationships
Healthy and productive relationships
Strong synergistic relationships
No relationship
Starting to engage
Establishing working partnerships
Healthy and productive partnerships
Strong synergistic partnerships, working to advance/ multiply missions in the nations.
